{"color": "cyan", "emoji": "\ud83d\udee0", "event_type": "Command Finished", "message": "completed, exit 0: /bin/zsh -lc 'rg -n \"vite|localhost:|docker compose|compose up|frontend\" README* docs infra -S'", "raw_event": {"item": {"aggregated_output": "README.md:40:- Frontend: React + Vite + TypeScript\nREADME.md:44:- Local orchestration: Docker Compose\nREADME.md:57:The repo is intended to run locally with Docker Compose. At the current scaffold stage:\nREADME.md:59:- `frontend/` contains a Vite React app served on `http://localhost:8566`\nREADME.md:60:- `backend/` contains a FastAPI app served on `http://localhost:8565`\nREADME.md:75:- syncs `frontend/node_modules`\nREADME.md:85:- `frontend` on `http://localhost:8566`\nREADME.md:86:- `backend` on `http://localhost:8565`\nREADME.md:88:- `postgres` on `localhost:8567`\nREADME.md:89:- `gcs` on `http://localhost:8568`\nREADME.md:103:- `make bootstrap`: first-run setup for hooks, local Python deps, frontend deps, and a local `secrets.yaml`\nREADME.md:104:- `make up`: build and start the Docker Compose stack in detached mode\nREADME.md:108:- `make format`: apply Prettier to the frontend and Ruff formatting to the backend\nREADME.md:110:- `make lint`: run frontend ESLint and backend Ruff lint checks\nREADME.md:111:- `make test`: run backend pytest and frontend Vitest\nREADME.md:112:- `make build`: run the frontend production build\nREADME.md:113:- `make check`: run formatting checks, lint, tests, and the frontend build in one pass\nREADME.md:119:2. make changes in `frontend/` or `backend/`\nREADME.md:126:For frontend-only work, `make frontend-format`, `make frontend-format-check`, `make frontend-lint`, `make frontend-test`, and `make frontend-build` are available as narrower targets. For backend-only work, use `make backend-format`, `make backend-format-check`, `make backend-lint`, `make backend-test`, and `make backend-storage-smoke`.\nREADME.md:128:## Docker Compose Local Stack\nREADME.md:141:`make reset` removes only those two data volumes so schema or seed-data changes can start from a clean slate without forcing frontend or QA dependency reinstallation. If you intentionally want a full compose wipe, including cached dependency volumes, `./scripts/dev-compose.sh down --volumes` remains available as the deeper reset path.\nREADME.md:151:- `STORYTELLER_GCS_PUBLIC_URL=http://localhost:8568`\nREADME.md:179:\u251c\u2500\u2500 frontend/\nREADME.md:191:- `frontend/`: browser client and TypeScript UI foundation\ninfra/README.md:7:- `compose/`: Docker Compose files and usage notes\ninfra/compose/docker-compose.yml:35:      - localhost:8568\ninfra/compose/docker-compose.yml:37:      - http://localhost:8568\ninfra/compose/docker-compose.yml:71:      STORYTELLER_GCS_PUBLIC_URL: http://localhost:8568\ninfra/compose/docker-compose.yml:114:      STORYTELLER_GCS_PUBLIC_URL: http://localhost:8568\ninfra/compose/docker-compose.yml:127:  frontend:\ninfra/compose/docker-compose.yml:129:      context: ../../frontend\ninfra/compose/docker-compose.yml:136:      VITE_DEV_PROXY_TARGET: http://backend:8565\ninfra/compose/docker-compose.yml:138:      - ../../frontend:/app\ninfra/compose/docker-compose.yml:139:      - frontend_node_modules:/app/node_modules\ninfra/compose/docker-compose.yml:161:      frontend:\ninfra/compose/docker-compose.yml:166:      TARGET_BASE_URL: http://frontend:8566\ninfra/compose/docker-compose.yml:173:  frontend_node_modules:\ninfra/compose/README.md:16:- `frontend` on `http://localhost:8566`\ninfra/compose/README.md:17:- `backend` on `http://localhost:8565`\ninfra/compose/README.md:19:- `postgres` on `localhost:8567`\ninfra/compose/README.md:20:- `gcs` on `http://localhost:8568`\ndocs/architecture-overview.md:14:React + Vite client\ndocs/architecture-overview.md:40:The frontend should only call the backend's API and subscribe to backend-owned progress events.\ndocs/architecture-overview.md:91:- `frontend/`: Vite React TypeScript app\ndocs/architecture-overview.md:96:- `infra/compose/docker-compose.yml`: local frontend, backend, PostgreSQL, file-backed GCS emulator, and browser QA services\ndocs/system-diagram.md:7:    Browser[\"Browser UI<br/>React + Vite<br/>sessions home, chat pane, workflow pane\"]\ndocs/secrets-and-local-config.md:41:The Docker Compose backend service mounts the repository at `/workspace` and sets:\ndocs/secrets-and-local-config.md:81:  public_url: http://localhost:8568\ndocs/secrets-and-local-config.md:89:    - http://localhost:8566\ndocs/secrets-and-local-config.md:139:The frontend never receives the Gemini API key. The browser only talks to the FastAPI backend, and all Gemini access stays in backend-owned services and adapters.\ndocs/genre-tone-catalog.md:33:hard-coding new options in the frontend.\ndocs/chat-action-echoes.md:39:- The frontend rebuilds transcript echoes from durable history in\ndocs/chat-action-echoes.md:40:  `frontend/src/features/session/chat/actionEchoes.ts`.\ndocs/contributing.md:3:Keep changes boring, typed, and easy to review. This repo is split between a React + TypeScript frontend and a FastAPI backend, so use the stack-specific tooling below instead of personal preferences.\ndocs/contributing.md:9:- `make lint`: run frontend ESLint and backend Ruff checks\ndocs/contributing.md:10:- `make test`: run backend pytest and frontend Vitest\ndocs/contributing.md:11:- `make check`: run formatting checks, lint, tests, and the frontend production build\ndocs/contributing.md:15:- `make frontend-format`, `make frontend-format-check`, `make frontend-lint`, `make frontend-test`, `make frontend-build`\ndocs/contributing.md:29:- Put durable workflow logic in backend services or repositories, not in route modules or frontend components.\ndocs/contributing.md:36:- Return structured error payloads from HTTP endpoints instead of ad hoc strings when the frontend needs to branch on the failure.\ndocs/contributing.md:38:- In the frontend, prefer explicit empty, loading, and error states over silent failure.\ndocs/contributing.md:42:- Keep hand-written source in `frontend/src/`, `backend/app/`, `backend/tests/`, `docs/`, and `scripts/`.\ndocs/contributing.md:43:- Treat generated output as disposable. Build artifacts belong in ignored directories such as `frontend/dist/`, coverage caches, or future runtime storage paths under `infra/persistence/`.\ndocs/frontend-design-foundation.md:1:# Frontend Design Foundation\ndocs/frontend-state-architecture.md:1:# Frontend State Architecture\ndocs/frontend-state-architecture.md:9:   - `frontend/src/features/session/sessionQueries.ts`\ndocs/frontend-state-architecture.md:13:   - `frontend/src/features/session/sessionRuntimeStore.ts`\ndocs/frontend-state-architecture.md:17:   - `frontend/src/features/session/SessionWorkspaceProvider.tsx`\ndocs/chat-to-ui-actions.md:9:The mirrored frontend parser and type layer live in\ndocs/chat-to-ui-actions.md:10:`frontend/src/features/session/chat/chatToUiActions.ts`.\ndocs/chat-to-ui-actions.md:75:- The frontend mirror rejects payloads that violate the default confirm-first\ndocs/product-brief.md:15:- Local-first development: the full stack should run locally through Docker Compose with persistent infrastructure.\ndocs/product-brief.md:68:- Frontend: React, Vite, TypeScript\ndocs/product-brief.md:72:- Local orchestration: Docker Compose\ndocs/adr/0001-core-runtime-architecture.md:28:- Model IDs stay centralized in backend settings and adapter code, not in frontend code or route handlers.\ndocs/adr/0001-core-runtime-architecture.md:57:- In local development, that object storage is the file-backed GCS emulator already defined in Docker Compose.\ndocs/adr/0001-core-runtime-architecture.md:109:- Put websocket endpoints under backend API ownership, not in the frontend dev server.\ndocs/domain-model.md:3:This document defines the durable business objects and workflow rules for a single story-creation session. The goal is to give the backend, frontend, migrations, and later AI orchestration code one shared contract for how a session progresses, pauses, rewinds, and resumes.\ndocs/domain-model.md:38:`resume_stage` is the key anti-guessing field. The backend computes it from durable stage states so the frontend does not need to infer where to reopen a session by looking at which panels happen to have data.\ndocs/domain-model.md:84:- `frontend/src/features/session/workflowStages.ts`\ndocs/domain-model.md:86:The backend remains the authority for validating transitions. The frontend should use the same literal IDs for rendering, navigation, and optimistic display only.\ndocs/domain-model.md:123:This is the behavior implemented by the `resolve_resume_stage` helper in both the backend and frontend contract files.\ndocs/domain-model.md:177:- Frontend mirror for rendering and client-side navigation: `frontend/src/features/session/workflowStages.ts`\ndocs/domain-model.md:185:- The backend service layer, not the frontend, decides whether a requested stage transition is valid for the current session snapshot.\n", "command": "/bin/zsh -lc 'rg -n \"vite|localhost:|docker compose|compose up|frontend\" README* docs infra -S'", "exit_code": 0, "id": "item_173", "status": "completed", "type": "command_execution"}, "type": "item.completed"}, "task_display_context": {"event_number": 358, "prompt_index": 57, "prompt_name": "56 \u2014 Revision History and Branch-Like Tracking for Plan Changes", "prompt_total": 100}, "timestap": "2026-04-02T04:41:25-07:00"}
{"color": "green", "emoji": "\ud83d\udcac", "event_type": "Agent Message", "message": "Using the `webapp-qa` skill for the last phase because this change adds session UI around revision history and restore, and I need browser-level evidence from the Docker Compose stack rather than only unit tests. Plan: 1. Add the missing...", "raw_event": {"item": {"id": "item_174", "text": "Using the `webapp-qa` skill for the last phase because this change adds session UI around revision history and restore, and I need browser-level evidence from the Docker Compose stack rather than only unit tests.\n\nPlan:\n1. Add the missing backend assertions around composition lineage and plan revision snapshots.\n2. Run targeted backend/frontend suites, then broader lint/build checks to catch integration issues.\n3. Start the local stack if needed, exercise the new revision history/restore flow in the browser, and capture screenshots/evidence.\n4. Commit a coherent checkpoint, then write the required reviewer summary as the final filesystem change.", "type": "agent_message"}, "type": "item.completed"}, "task_display_context": {"event_number": 359, "prompt_index": 57, "prompt_name": "56 \u2014 Revision History and Branch-Like Tracking for Plan Changes", "prompt_total": 100}, "timestap": "2026-04-02T04:41:37-07:00"}
{"color": "cyan", "emoji": "\ud83d\udee0", "event_type": "Command Started", "message": "in progress: /bin/zsh -lc \"sed -n '1,220p' README.md\"", "raw_event": {"item": {"aggregated_output": "", "command": "/bin/zsh -lc \"sed -n '1,220p' README.md\"", "exit_code": null, "id": "item_175", "status": "in_progress", "type": "command_execution"}, "type": "item.started"}, "task_display_context": {"event_number": 360, "prompt_index": 57, "prompt_name": "56 \u2014 Revision History and Branch-Like Tracking for Plan Changes", "prompt_total": 100}, "timestap": "2026-04-02T04:41:37-07:00"}
{"color": "cyan", "emoji": "\ud83d\udee0", "event_type": "Command Finished", "message": "completed, exit 0: /bin/zsh -lc \"sed -n '1,220p' README.md\"", "raw_event": {"item": {"aggregated_output": "# Storyteller\n\nStoryteller is a local-first, full-stack app for creating bedtime stories from first idea to finished text and finished narration audio. The product is session-based: the first meaningful screen is a past-sessions view where a user can resume work in progress, reopen a completed story, or start a new session.\n\nThis repository currently contains the first scaffold for that system. The project charter in this README and the supporting docs define the product and architecture that later prompts will implement.\n\n## Product Vision\n\nThe app should feel like a guided bedtime story studio, not a generic prompt box. A user should be able to:\n\n- See past sessions first and continue where they left off.\n- Collaborate through both chat and direct UI controls.\n- Move through a structured planning workflow before long-form writing starts.\n- Watch story composition and audio generation progress in real time.\n- Return later to read, listen, download, or revise completed work.\n\nThe tone of the product should stay calm, readable, and trustworthy. Wonder, mystery, and adventure are welcome, but bedtime suitability is a hard requirement: emotional stakes should resolve safely and the ending should feel restful.\n\n## Required Story Workflow\n\nThe application is being built around this ordered workflow:\n\n1. Genre selection\n2. Tone selection\n3. Story setup / free-form brief\n4. Story pitches\n5. Character sheet\n6. Save-the-Cat beat sheet\n7. Story setup preferences such as word count, runtime, and chapters\n8. Composition\n9. Audio configuration and audio generation\n10. Finalize / read / listen / download\n\nEach stage must be durable, resumable, and editable. Chat messages can propose actions in the workflow, and direct UI actions must also be reflected back into the session chat log as compact summaries.\n\n## Fixed Technical Decisions\n\nThese choices are not optional for this project:\n\n- Frontend: React + Vite + TypeScript\n- Backend: Python + FastAPI\n- Structured data: PostgreSQL\n- Blob storage: file-backed GCS emulator in local development\n- Local orchestration: Docker Compose\n- Secrets handling: local `secrets.yaml`, never committed to git\n- AI access: Gemini 3.1 family behind backend-owned adapters and services\n\nTwo architectural rules follow from those constraints:\n\n- The browser must never hold provider secrets or call Gemini directly.\n- Long-running story composition and narration generation must be durable background jobs with resumable server-side state.\n\nMore detail is in [docs/product-brief.md](/Users/kevin/code/storyteller/docs/product-brief.md), [docs/architecture-overview.md](/Users/kevin/code/storyteller/docs/architecture-overview.md), [docs/system-diagram.md](/Users/kevin/code/storyteller/docs/system-diagram.md), and [docs/adr/0001-core-runtime-architecture.md](/Users/kevin/code/storyteller/docs/adr/0001-core-runtime-architecture.md).\n\n## Local Development Expectations\n\nThe repo is intended to run locally with Docker Compose. At the current scaffold stage:\n\n- `frontend/` contains a Vite React app served on `http://localhost:8566`\n- `backend/` contains a FastAPI app served on `http://localhost:8565`\n- `infra/compose/` holds the canonical Compose file for local orchestration\n- `tools/webapp-qa/` contains the browser automation container used for local UI verification\n\nBootstrap a new clone with:\n\n```bash\nmake bootstrap\n```\n\nThat command:\n\n- creates `secrets.yaml` from `secrets.example.yaml` if it does not exist yet\n- installs the repo-managed Git hooks\n- creates or refreshes `backend/.venv`\n- syncs `frontend/node_modules`\n\nThen start the local stack with:\n\n```bash\nmake up\n```\n\nThe local Compose stack includes:\n\n- `frontend` on `http://localhost:8566`\n- `backend` on `http://localhost:8565`\n- `worker` for durable background job execution\n- `postgres` on `localhost:8567`\n- `gcs` on `http://localhost:8568`\n\n`secrets.yaml` is already gitignored and reserved for local-only credentials. `make bootstrap` will create it from `secrets.example.yaml` when needed, but you still need to replace the placeholder Gemini API key before using AI-backed workflows. The repo-managed Git hook blocks accidental commits of `secrets.yaml`, `.env` files, and obvious live key material. The compose file uses development defaults for Postgres and the GCS emulator, while the backend loads secrets from the repo-root `secrets.yaml` at container startup.\n\n## Daily Workflow\n\nThe repository now exposes a small top-level command surface through the root `Makefile`:\n\n```bash\nmake help\n```\n\nThe most common daily commands are:\n\n- `make bootstrap`: first-run setup for hooks, local Python deps, frontend deps, and a local `secrets.yaml`\n- `make up`: build and start the Docker Compose stack in detached mode\n- `make logs`: follow the compose logs without restarting anything\n- `make down`: stop the stack and preserve local Postgres and fake GCS data\n- `make reset`: stop the stack and remove only the Postgres and fake GCS data volumes\n- `make format`: apply Prettier to the frontend and Ruff formatting to the backend\n- `make format-check`: verify formatting for both stacks without changing files\n- `make lint`: run frontend ESLint and backend Ruff lint checks\n- `make test`: run backend pytest and frontend Vitest\n- `make build`: run the frontend production build\n- `make check`: run formatting checks, lint, tests, and the frontend build in one pass\n- `make backend-storage-smoke`: round-trip a sample object through the local storage emulator\n\nSuggested daily loop:\n\n1. `make up`\n2. make changes in `frontend/` or `backend/`\n3. `make format` before or after a focused edit pass\n4. `make logs` when you need live service output\n5. `make test` for targeted automated coverage\n6. `make check` before handing work off or committing\n7. `make down` when you are done\n\nFor frontend-only work, `make frontend-format`, `make frontend-format-check`, `make frontend-lint`, `make frontend-test`, and `make frontend-build` are available as narrower targets. For backend-only work, use `make backend-format`, `make backend-format-check`, `make backend-lint`, `make backend-test`, and `make backend-storage-smoke`.\n\n## Docker Compose Local Stack\n\nUse `make up`, `make down`, and `make logs` for the common compose workflow. The existing wrapper script remains the canonical compose entrypoint underneath those targets, so advanced commands can still go through:\n\n```bash\n./scripts/dev-compose.sh ps\n```\n\nPersistent data lives in named Docker volumes:\n\n- `storyteller_postgres_data` for PostgreSQL\n- `storyteller_gcs_data` for the file-backed GCS emulator\n\n`make reset` removes only those two data volumes so schema or seed-data changes can start from a clean slate without forcing frontend or QA dependency reinstallation. If you intentionally want a full compose wipe, including cached dependency volumes, `./scripts/dev-compose.sh down --volumes` remains available as the deeper reset path.\n\nThe backend receives the local infrastructure coordinates through environment variables in Compose:\n\n- `STORYTELLER_DATABASE_URL=postgresql+psycopg://storyteller:storyteller@postgres:5432/storyteller`\n- `STORYTELLER_GCS_ENDPOINT=http://gcs:4443`\n- `STORYTELLER_GCS_SESSIONS_BUCKET_NAME=storyteller-sessions`\n- `STORYTELLER_GCS_AUDIO_BUCKET_NAME=storyteller-audio`\n- `STORYTELLER_GCS_EXPORTS_BUCKET_NAME=storyteller-exports`\n- `STORYTELLER_GCS_PROJECT_ID=storyteller-local`\n- `STORYTELLER_GCS_PUBLIC_URL=http://localhost:8568`\n\nThe backend settings layer merges defaults, `secrets.yaml`, and environment variables in that order. More detail is in [docs/secrets-and-local-config.md](/Users/kevin/code/storyteller/docs/secrets-and-local-config.md).\n\nBucket roles and stable object-key conventions for drafts, audio, exports, and debug artifacts live\nin [docs/storage-buckets-and-prefixes.md](/Users/kevin/code/storyteller/docs/storage-buckets-and-prefixes.md).\n\nThe root `Makefile` and the scripts under `scripts/` are written for `bash` and are intended for macOS, Linux, or WSL-based development environments. They expect `make`, Docker, `npm`, and Python 3.10 or newer to be available locally.\n\n## Repository Shape\n\n```text\n.\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 backend/\n\u2502   \u251c\u2500\u2500 app/\n\u2502   \u2502   \u251c\u2500\u2500 api/\n\u2502   \u2502   \u251c\u2500\u2500 db/\n\u2502   \u2502   \u251c\u2500\u2500 models/\n\u2502   \u2502   \u251c\u2500\u2500 services/\n\u2502   \u2502   \u251c\u2500\u2500 settings/\n\u2502   \u2502   \u251c\u2500\u2500 main.py\n\u2502   \u2502   \u2514\u2500\u2500 worker/\n\u2502   \u251c\u2500\u2500 tests/\n\u2502   \u251c\u2500\u2500 migrations/\n\u2502   \u251c\u2500\u2500 Dockerfile\n\u2502   \u251c\u2500\u2500 README.md\n\u2502   \u2514\u2500\u2500 requirements.txt\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 docs/\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 frontend/\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 infra/\n\u2502   \u251c\u2500\u2500 compose/\n\u2502   \u2502   \u2514\u2500\u2500 docker-compose.yml\n\u2502   \u2514\u2500\u2500 persistence/\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 prompts/\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 scripts/\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 test-assets/\n\u2514\u2500\u2500 tools/\n    \u2514\u2500\u2500 webapp-qa/\n```\n\n- `frontend/`: browser client and TypeScript UI foundation\n- `backend/`: FastAPI API code, settings, services, tests, worker home, and migration home\n- `infra/`: Compose definitions and infrastructure notes\n- `docs/`: product notes, architecture notes, and future ADRs\n- `scripts/`: developer entrypoints such as `dev-compose.sh`\n- `test-assets/`: reusable fixtures for UI, audio, and integration testing\n- `prompts/`: sequential build prompts and task summaries\n- `tools/`: local QA and developer tooling\n\n## What Success Looks Like\n\nA new engineer should be able to open this repository and quickly understand:\n\n- the first screen is the past-sessions home for resume, edit, and create flows\n- the story workflow is staged and ordered\n- the final product writes stories and generates narration audio durably\n- the backend and worker own AI access, long-running jobs, and persistent state\n", "command": "/bin/zsh -lc \"sed -n '1,220p' README.md\"", "exit_code": 0, "id": "item_175", "status": "completed", "type": "command_execution"}, "type": "item.completed"}, "task_display_context": {"event_number": 361, "prompt_index": 57, "prompt_name": "56 \u2014 Revision History and Branch-Like Tracking for Plan Changes", "prompt_total": 100}, "timestap": "2026-04-02T04:41:37-07:00"}
